05145nam a22007575i 9780824890186DE-B159720220110023848.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220110t20212021hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248901867 a10.1515/97808248901862doi  a(DE-B1597)577716  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aD769.8.A6bC54 2021eb 7aHIS0361402bisacsh04a940.539690899561 aCoffman, Tom, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInclusion :bHow Hawai‘i Protected Japanese Americans from Mass Internment, Transformed Itself, and Changed America /cTom Coffman. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b22 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFollowing December 7, 1941, when the United States government interned 120,000 people of Japanese ancestry evicted from scattered settlements throughout the West Coast states, why was a much larger number concentrated in the Hawaiian Islands war zone not similarly incarcerated? At the root of the story is an inclusive community that worked from the ground up to protect an embattled segment of its population. Where the onset of World War II surprised the American public, war with Japan arrived in Hawai‘i in slow motion. Responding to numerous signs of impending conflict, a Council for Interracial Unity mapped two goals: Minimize internment and maximize inclusion in the war effort. The Council’s aspirational work was expressed in a widely repeated saying: "How we get along during the war will determine how we get along when the war is over." The Army Command of Hawai‘i, reassured by first-hand acquaintances, came to believe "Trust breeds trust." Where most histories have shielded President Franklin D. Roosevelt from direct responsibility for the U.S. mainland internment, his relentless demands for a mass removal from Hawai‘i—ultimately thwarted—reveal him as author and actor. In making sense of the disparity between Island and mainland, Inclusion unravels the deep history of the U.S. “sabotage psychosis,” dissecting why many continental Americans still believe Japan succeeded at Pearl Harbor because of the unseen hand of Japanese saboteurs. Contrary to the explanation of hysteria as the cause of the internment, Inclusion documents how a high-level plan of mass removal actually was pitched to Hawai‘i prior to December 7, only to be rejected.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 0aJapanese AmericansxForced removal and internment, 1942-1945. 0aJapanese AmericanszHawaiixHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJapanese Americans. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xParticipation, Japanese American. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2z978311074335708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073968840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780824890186zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824890186423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824890186/original  a978-3-11-073968-8  University of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-074335-7  DG Plus P